1495":"1495","<1432>":"1432","1407":"1407","Angerming, Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Angmering, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Angmering, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Angmering, Sussex, England":"Angmering, Sussex, England","<Of, Angmering, Sussex, England>":"Angmering, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cook","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a cook, a seller of cooked meats, or a keeper of an eating house, from Middle English <i>cok</i>, <i>coke</i>, <i>cook</i>, <i>couk</i>, <i>cuk(e)</i> (Old English <i>cōc</i>) ‘cook’ or ‘seller of cooked foods’. See also   Kew  .","Irish and Scottish: usually identical in origin with the English name (see 1 above), but in some cases a shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Cúg</b> ‘son of Hugo’ (see   McCook  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning ‘cook’, such as German and Jewish   Koch  , Dutch   Kook  , Polish <b>Kucharz</b> and   Kucharczyk  , Slovenian and Croatian   Kuhar  , North German   Kuk  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Cookson","meanings":["English (Lancashire): from Middle English <i>cok</i> ‘cook’ or the surname <i>Cook</i> + <i>son</i>, denoting either ‘son of (the) cook’ or ‘son of (a man called) Cook’. See   Cook  ."]},{"name":"Cocke","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>cok</i> (Old English and Old French <i>coc</i>) ‘rooster’.","patronymic from the Old French and Middle English personal name <i>Cok</i>, of uncertain origin but perhaps derived from the word in 1 above."]},{"name":"Coke","meanings":["English: variant of   Cook   or   Cocke  .","Americanized form of German   Koke   or   Koch  ."]},{"name":"Kuhar","meanings":["Slovenian and Croatian: occupational name for a cook, from <i>kuhar</i>, a derivative of <i>kuhati</i> ‘to cook’. Compare   Cook  .","Americanized form of Slovak <b>Kuchár</b> ‘cook’ (see   Kuchar  ) and of its Ukrainian and Rusyn cognate <b>Kukhar</b>."]},{"name":"Cooke","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Cook  .","History: Francis Cooke (died 1663) and his eldest son John were passengers on the <i>Mayflower</i> in 1621; they were joined two years later by Francis's wife and other children. In the words of William Bradford, he lived long enough ‘to see his children's children have children’."]},{"name":"Kew","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name from Old French <i>queu</i>, <i>keu</i>, <i>kieu</i>, <i>cu</i> ‘cook’, i.e. one who sold cooked meat, keeper of an eating house.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Caieu, a lost town in northern France, in the vicinity of Boulogne-sur-Mer.","Irish: shortened Ulster variant of   McHugh  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Cook was born in 1411, in Angmering, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Cook, was 24 and her mother, Mrs John Cook, was 25. She married Sir Edward Bilton in 1432, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1433, in Sussex, England, at the age of 22."},"et":{"1411–1433":"1411–1433","1407–1433":"1407–1433","1433–1495":"1433–1495","1387–Male":"1387–Surnud","1387–Female":"1387–Surnud","1411":"1411","1433":"1433","1387":"1387","1495":"1495","<1432>":"1432","1407":"1407","Angerming, Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Angmering, Sussex, England, United Kingdom":"Angmering, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Angmering, Sussex, England":"Angmering, Sussex, England","<Of, Angmering, Sussex, England>":"An